# Intl.ListFormat

The **`Intl.ListFormat`** object enables language-sensitive list formatting.

## [Try it](#try%5Fit)

## [Constructor](#constructor)

[Intl.ListFormat()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Intl/ListFormat/ListFormat)

Creates a new `Intl.ListFormat` object.

## [Static methods](#static%5Fmethods)

[Intl.ListFormat.supportedLocalesOf()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Intl/ListFormat/supportedLocalesOf)

Returns an array containing those of the provided locales that are supported without having to fall back to the runtime's default locale.

## [Instance properties](#instance%5Fproperties)

These properties are defined on `Intl.ListFormat.prototype` and shared by all `Intl.ListFormat` instances.

[Intl.ListFormat.prototype.constructor](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Object/constructor)

The constructor function that created the instance object. For `Intl.ListFormat` instances, the initial value is the [Intl.ListFormat](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Intl/ListFormat/ListFormat) constructor.

`Intl.ListFormat.prototype[@@toStringTag]`

The initial value of the [@@toStringTag](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Symbol/toStringTag) property is the string `"Intl.ListFormat"`. This property is used in [Object.prototype.toString()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Object/toString).

## [Instance methods](#instance%5Fmethods)

[Intl.ListFormat.prototype.format()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Intl/ListFormat/format)

Returns a language-specific formatted string representing the elements of the list.

[Intl.ListFormat.prototype.formatToParts()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Intl/ListFormat/formatToParts)

Returns an array of objects representing the different components that can be used to format a list of values in a locale-aware fashion.

[Intl.ListFormat.prototype.resolvedOptions()](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Intl/ListFormat/resolvedOptions)

Returns a new object with properties reflecting the locale and style formatting options computed during the construction of the current [Intl.ListFormat](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global%5FObjects/Intl/ListFormat) object.

## [Examples](#examples)

### [Using format](#using%5Fformat)

The following example shows how to create a List formatter using the English language.

```
const list = ["Motorcycle", "Bus", "Car"];

console.log(
  new Intl.ListFormat("en-GB", { style: "long", type: "conjunction" }).format(
    list,
  ),
);
// Motorcycle, Bus and Car

console.log(
  new Intl.ListFormat("en-GB", { style: "short", type: "disjunction" }).format(
    list,
  ),
);
// Motorcycle, Bus or Car

console.log(
  new Intl.ListFormat("en-GB", { style: "narrow", type: "unit" }).format(list),
);
// Motorcycle Bus Car

```

### [Using formatToParts](#using%5Fformattoparts)

The following example shows how to create a List formatter returning formatted parts

```
const list = ["Motorcycle", "Bus", "Car"];
console.log(
  new Intl.ListFormat("en-GB", {
    style: "long",
    type: "conjunction",
  }).formatToParts(list),
);

// [ { "type": "element", "value": "Motorcycle" },
//   { "type": "literal", "value": ", " },
//   { "type": "element", "value": "Bus" },
//   { "type": "literal", "value": ", and " },
//   { "type": "element", "value": "Car" } ];

```

